    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2763336764" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2763336764" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16855847-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359307439p2/16855847.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2763336764?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/16855847-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099512158" href="/book/show/1320341.The_Leopard">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2763336764" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4056765752830717639">The first time I knew about &quot;The Leopard&quot; was spring 1964, when I saw the film starring Burt Lancaster and Claudia Cardinale, bracketed by Alain Delon as Tancredo, and directed by Luchino Visconti, who also, directed “The Stranger” based on Camus’ novel. When a genius gets into the middle of a thing, the wheel just keeps turning letting the sparks fly.<br/><br/>I would go each afternoon after my last class at Sam Houston State University in Huntsville, Texas, and sit alone in the theater, which was locate</span>
  <span id="freeText4056765752830717639" style="display:none">The first time I knew about "The Leopard" was spring 1964, when I saw the film starring Burt Lancaster and Claudia Cardinale, bracketed by Alain Delon as Tancredo, and directed by Luchino Visconti, who also, directed “The Stranger” based on Camus’ novel. When a genius gets into the middle of a thing, the wheel just keeps turning letting the sparks fly.<br /><br />I would go each afternoon after my last class at Sam Houston State University in Huntsville, Texas, and sit alone in the theater, which was located just around the town square from the Cafe Texan where I would go for my only meal of the day, huevos rancheros (Arriba!). Since I had the theater pretty much to myself I went three times that week, twice for Claudia Cardinale and the third time because of the rich story of revolution and survival and, of course, romantic love—that swift, terrible emotion that can shake you to the core.<br /><br />Several years later I found a paperback copy tucked away in the shelves of the little library at the school where I was teaching in the remote bush of Zambia. I had been becoming more aware of how inevitably improbable change could, and must, come. College studies had not taught me this so much, but this tiny novel “The Leopard” had shown me plainly what the future must feel like.<br /><br />If one is lucky, one gets to know in one’s youth a wise elderly person who passes on a spark from the fire that once lit their world, such as Don Fabrizio Corbera with Tancredo (in my mind Burt Lancaster with Alain Delon).<br /><br />I should learn Italian and reread this sensitive, beautiful novel evoking a time that moderns might easily forget. If you are enchanted by the Mediterranean, you will be enchanted by “Il Gattopardo”. <br /><br />(Ah, those sweet days of adventure and romance! How can I ever thank you?)</span>
  <a data-text-id="4056765752830717639" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review2763336764">
